        <stimulus>"The growth of a large business is merely survival of the fittest... The American Beauty rose can be produced in the splendor and fragrance which bring cheer to its beholder only by sacrificing the early buds which grow up around it."
- John D. Rockefeller, 1902</stimulus>
        <prompt>Which Progressive Era policy most directly challenged this view?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">The Sherman Antitrust Act</option>
            <option letter="b">The Pure Food and Drug Act</option>
            <option letter="c">The Federal Reserve Act</option>
            <option letter="d">The Adamson Act</option>
        </options>
        <answer>a</answer>
        <explanation>The Sherman Antitrust Act directly challenged Rockefeller's defense of monopolies by declaring them illegal and subject to government regulation.</explanation>
    </question>
    <question>
        <stimulus>[Photographs showing children working in textile mills alongside newspaper headlines about state-level child labor laws, 1900-1916]</stimulus>
        <prompt>These images most directly contributed to:</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">The Keating-Owen Act</option>
            <option letter="b">The Federal Reserve Act</option>
            <option letter="c">The Clayton Antitrust Act</option>
            <option letter="d">The Hepburn Act</option>
        </options>
        <answer>a</answer>
        <explanation>Photographs documenting child labor conditions helped build public support for the Keating-Owen Act of 1916, the first federal child labor law.</explanation>
    </question>
